snippet.textDisplay: EUFA are being really unfair on City and we could get banned from CL! But look what happened - just prior to FFP Sheik Mansour took over based on a careful plan and 35 days later a coach and horses was driven through that investment and plan with a new set of rules. . FFP seems like a restrictive practice which can  stop investment and development, keep the status quo. City owner gives his own company 50 million Etihad and says add that to our sponsorship of City and EUFA say no - ridiculous.  City have made the single most important and responsible investment in a community ever in the history of sport. Transforming a whole area of Manchester and they have not bought in Ronaldo, Messi, Neymar Mbappe and the like - we won the league with four players Mark Hughes bought ffs. EUFA cut City any slack for our responsible approach? For creating 2000 new jobs, building 6000 new homes on the old Maine Road site in Moss Side? A new school? A library?  A community centre? A sports complex with 8 pitches? A women's team? 140 charity projects? A cerebral palsy team? (wheelchairs for that are amazing) A blind person's team? Free use of the pitches for 300 local school kids? Yeah EUFA don't mention all that do they!  They just assume arabs are up to no good. It is they that should rethink their approach to City - they might realise what a great club it is with owners keen to do the right thing. By the way I did not see them sanctioning Man U for allowing the Glazers to dump all the debt (900 million) on the club and then the club pays it all back - their personal debts!!!  City are doing everything right and very very responsibly and EUFA should be encouraging this kind of investment. Also why ban us that just hurts the fans players, tv viewers and football fans. FFP was not designed to prevent investment like City's but stop debts like United. EUFA should be looking to have City as a main partner - a responsible investor, the like of which is unheard of. Crikey redirecting £50 million of sponsorship money on one side to £1.5 billion on infracstructure and the community on the other - you'd think EUFA would be much more lenient. Fans and players do not deserve it!! .

snippet.textDisplay: Most of the time i don't agree with these guys but their analysis of this game is pretty much spot on. It's true Real Madrid have been at their best this season when they're being conservative. And that's the reason Zidane did not decide to commit numbers forward much against City. In fact, almost immediately after Real Madrid scored the first goal and pushed for a second he reverted to being conservative again by taking his best attacker, Vinicius off. And, as Alejandro said: that conservative defending style of play is not the Real Madrid way. They did defend great in the first halve of this season but, because defending is not in their nature, counting on their defense to win game was going to come bite them at some point. That's whats happening right now. They dominate games with possession as they did against celta, levante and even City in the first halve (they had 71! percent in the first 30 minutes or so against a Guardiola-team, i'm not kidding) but as soon as they do get a goal, they sit back hoping to score on the counter. Barring some games during the jose mourinho era, that 'park the bus' style of play is the exact opposite of what this club stands for. Real has always been abt going forward and scoring goals. The biggest problem they have now is they don't have anyone that can convert the chances they create. Personally, i think that issue will only be corrected when Mbappé (are some other proven goalscorer) arrives

snippet.textDisplay:
Sometimes, when fans see 'chances', they assume that a team should have won and were unfortunate not to. A lot of times, finishing chances is about being composed and clinical. If you play Bayern Munich, you can create 15 good chances all you want, but if you don't take them........guess what, Lewandowski doesn't need 15 chances. He's far more likely to convert 1/3.


After the match, we'll hear "Bayern should have lost, Team X was the better side. Bayern got lucky!". No, Lewandowski is a far better finisher than Team X has, and it was never likely going to matter how many chances they had.
